"variants":[{"name":"Drews","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Erwin, Gerhard, Gunter, Hans, Heinz, Helmut, Otto, Reinhold, Bernd, Detlef, Egon, Erna.","English: variant of   Drew   with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. This surname is also found in Guernsey in the Channel Islands.","Americanized form of German, Danish, and Dutch   Drewes  ."]},{"name":"Drewer","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from the Old French personal name <i>Droart</i>, <i>Drouart</i> (which is probably from ancient Germanic <i>Droghard</i>, with the first element as in   Drew   + <i>hard</i> ‘brave, hardy’)."]},{"name":"Drewett","meanings":["English (Wiltshire, Berkshire, and Surrey): of Norman origin, from the Old French personal name <i>Druet</i>, a diminutive of <i>Drue</i>, <i>Dreu</i> (from ancient Germanic <i>Drogo</i>); see   Drew   1. Alternatively, the name may be from a diminutive of Old French <i>dru</i> ‘lover’; see   Drew   4."]},{"name":"Dronet","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Alcee, Desire, Olympe.","French (mainly Loire-Atlantique): from a diminutive of the personal name <i>Dron</i>, derived from the ancient Germanic name <i>Drogo</i>, a short form of compound names based on the element <i>drog</i>, presumably meaning ‘battle’ (see also   Drew  )."]},{"name":"Droz","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Aida, Cruz Maria, Diego, Jose, Miguel, Milagros, Nydia, Osvaldo, Rodriguez, Vidal.","French: from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Drogo</i>, a short form of compound names based on the element <i>drog</i>, presumably meaning ‘battle’ (see also   Drew  ). This surname is also found in Puerto Rico."]},{"name":"Drea","meanings":["Irish (Kilkenny): shortened Anglicized form of <b>Ó Draoi</b> (see   Drew  )."]},{"name":"Montague","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): habitational name from either Montaigu-le-bois (Manche) or Montaigu (Manche, Aisne), named with Old French <i>mont</i> ‘hill’ + <i>agu</i> ‘pointed’ (from Latin <i>acutus</i>). Drogo de Montagud was a companion of William the Conqueror and founder of the <b>Montagu(e)</b> family, among whom the personal name <i>Drogo</i> was revived in the 19th century. Another family of the name <b>Monatgu</b> have held the titles of Duke of Montagu, Earl of Sandwich, Earl and Duke of Manchester, Earl of Halifax, and Earl of Beaulieu, and.","Irish: adopted as equivalent of Gaelic <b>Mac Taidhg</b> (see   McTigue  )."]},{"name":"Drouin","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Marcel, Armand, Benoit, Jacques, Andre, Clermont, Emile, Gaston, Gilles, Ovide, Pierre, Serge.","French: from a pet form of the Old French personal name <i>Droue</i>, a variant of <i>Dreue</i>, which is from the ancient Germanic name <i>Drogo</i>, a short form of compound names based on the element <i>drog</i>, presumably meaning ‘battle’ (see also   Drew  ). Compare   Derouen  ,   Derouin  , and   Tron  ."]},{"name":"Drury","meanings":["English (Lincolnshire): variant of   Drury  ."]},{"name":"Drouhard","meanings":["French:","from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Droghard</i>, composed of the elements <i>drog</i> (presumably meaning ‘battle’; see also   Drew  ) and <i>hard</i> ‘hard, strong’.","alternatively, a derivative of the ancient Germanic name <i>Drogo</i>, a short form of compound names like <i>Droghard</i> (see 1 above)."]}]},{"name":"Nancy","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Of uncertain origin. From the 18th century it is clearly used as a pet form of   Ann   (  see  Nan  ), but it may originally have been a similar formation deriving from the common medieval given name   Annis  , a vernacular form of   Agnes .  Nowadays it is an independent name, and was especially popular in America in the 1930s, 40s, and 50s."],"variants":[{"name":"Nancie","meanings":["Of uncertain origin. From the 18th century it is clearly used as a pet form of   Ann   (  see  Nan  ), but it may originally have been a similar formation deriving from the common medieval given name   Annis  , a vernacular form of   Agnes .  Nowadays it is an independent name, and was especially popular in America in the 1930s, 40s, and 50s."]},{"name":"Nanci","meanings":["Of uncertain origin. From the 18th century it is clearly used as a pet form of   Ann   (  see  Nan  ), but it may originally have been a similar formation deriving from the common medieval given name   Annis  , a vernacular form of   Agnes .  Nowadays it is an independent name, and was especially popular in America in the 1930s, 40s, and 50s."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs Nancy Drew was born about 1605, in England, United Kingdom. She married William Drew about 1626, in Devon, Clackmannanshire, Scotland. They were the parents of at least 5 sons."},"et":{"about 1605–":"umbes 1605–Surnud","1598–1657":"1598–1657","1627–1669":"1627–1669","1630–1694":"1630–1694","1632–1694":"1632–1694","1633–1674":"1633–1674","1635–1669":"1635–1669","1605–Female":"1605–Surnud","1635":"1635","1657":"1657","       1633":"1633","about 1626":"umbes 1626","1633":"1633","about 1605":"umbes 1605","1632":"1632","about 1635":"umbes 1635","1598":"1598","1674":"1674","1630":"1630","1694":"1694","about 1630":"umbes 1630","1627":"1627","1605":"1605","1669":"1669",", Devonshire, England":"Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Devonshire, England":"Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Devenshire, England":"Devon, Clackmannanshire, Scotland","England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Devon, England":"Devon, England"},"fi":{"about 1605–":"noin 1605–Kuollut","1598–1657":"1598–1657","1627–1669":"1627–1669","1630–1694":"1630–1694","1632–1694":"1632–1694","1633–1674":"1633–1674","1635–1669":"1635–1669","1605–Female":"1605–Kuollut","1635":"1635","1657":"1657","       1633":"1633","about 1626":"noin 1626","1633":"1633","about 1605":"noin 1605","1632":"1632","about 1635":"noin 1635","1598":"1598","1674":"1674","1630":"1630","1